🧭 Project Overview

In this exercise, we install and configure Ansible, a powerful open-source automation tool used for configuration management, application deployment, and infrastructure orchestration.

Ansible is widely used in DevOps because it enables agentless automation over SSH, making server management scalable and efficient.

🎯 Objective
Understand Ansible architecture
Install Ansible on a control node
Verify installation
Understand inventory and basic usage
Reinforce automation fundamentals in DevOps
🧰 Environment
Linux control node (CentOS / Ubuntu)
SSH access to managed nodes
sudo/root privileges required
Python installed (dependency for Ansible)
📌 Concept Explanation

Ansible works on a simple architecture:

Control Node (Ansible installed)
        ↓ SSH
Managed Nodes (Target servers)
Key Features:
Agentless (no software installed on target servers)
Uses SSH for communication
Uses YAML for configuration (playbooks)
Idempotent (safe to run multiple times)
🛠️ Implementation Steps
1. Update system packages
sudo apt update -y

or

sudo yum update -y
2. Install Ansible
Ubuntu / Debian:
sudo apt install ansible -y
CentOS / RHEL:

Enable EPEL repository first:

sudo yum install epel-release -y

Then install Ansible:

sudo yum install ansible -y
3. Verify installation
ansible --version
🔍 Expected Output
ansible [core 2.x.x]
4. Understand Ansible inventory

Default inventory file:

/etc/ansible/hosts
Example inventory:
[webservers]
192.168.1.10
192.168.1.11

[dbservers]
192.168.1.20
5. Test Ansible connectivity
ansible all -m ping
🔍 Expected Output
192.168.1.10 | SUCCESS => {"ping": "pong"}
🔐 Security Insight

Ansible is powerful because it:

Uses SSH (no agents required)
Executes commands remotely
Requires secure key-based authentication
Can modify entire infrastructure at scale
Security best practices:
Use SSH keys (not passwords)
Limit inventory access
Use Ansible Vault for secrets
Restrict sudo privileges carefully
